setting up bidirectional, passwordless SSH authentication between two machines.
### 1. Configuration on Machine 1
```bash
# Generate the SSH key pair (Public and Private keys)
ssh-keygen
# Copy Machine 1's public key to Machine 2 to enable passwordless login
ssh-copy-id ubuntu@<IP_of_M2>
```
### 2. Configuration on Machine 2
```bash
# Generate the SSH key pair
ssh-keygen
# Copy Machine 2's public key back to Machine 1
ssh-copy-id ubuntu@<IP_of_M1>
```
### 3. SSH Daemon Configuration Changes (To be done on BOTH machines)
```bash
# Open the SSH daemon configuration file
sudo vim /etc/ssh/sshd_config
```
#### Inside /etc/ssh/sshd_config, make the following modifications:
```text
# Comment out password authentication to enforce key-based login
# PasswordAuthentication yes
# Uncomment or add this line to explicitly allow public key authentication
PubkeyAuthentication yes
```
```bash
# Save and exit vim using ':wq'
# Restart the SSH service to apply changes
sudo systemctl restart ssh
```
